    <title>Combined summary - On the scalability issues of onboarding millions of LN mobile clients</title>
    <updated>2023-06-14T01:24:28.179188+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2020-May/017818.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Bitcoin developers are currently discussing the future of light client protocols and full nodes in Bitcoin's security model. The scalability of light client protocols for Bitcoin's Lightning Network (LN) is the main topic of discussion in an email exchange between Antoine Riard and Andrés G. Aragoneses on May 5, 2020. The shift towards LN may attract a lot of adoption without users running a full-node due to its fast, affordable, confidential, censorship-resistant payment services. However, this poses challenges, particularly in terms of security and privacy.One of the bottlenecks is likely the number of full-nodes being willingly to dedicate resources to serve those clients. To combat these issues, various proposals have been made, such as exploring the feasibility of running full nodes on everyday phones, implementing fork anomalies detection, and introducing monetary compensation for servicing filters. Additionally, there is a demand for a peer service model between "full public" and "owner only" interfaces, which would enable low-cost ways to serve peer services to people with explicit permission, without giving them full administrative access to the node.There is also a debate over whether the adoption of LN could shift the trust-minimization of Bitcoin's security model from running a full node. Some argue that it may compromise Bitcoin's security, while others believe it could attract a lot of adoption without users running a full node. Cheaper and more efficient protocols like BIP 157 may face a bottleneck due to insufficient full-nodes willing to serve those clients, which could lead to centralized services. To address this issue, monetary compensation may be introduced in exchange for servicing filters to price chain access resources. However, how to avoid such a "chain access" market from turning into an oligopoly is an open question.The conversation also discusses the possibility of Lightning replacing centralized custodial services, allowing for scalability and maintaining noncustodiality. However, evaluating economic weight in Lightning is difficult due to the different chain views of both parties. The discussion then moves on to discuss the implementation of backup servers that are publicly-facing rather than privately-owned, but ensuring uniform distribution is challenging in a free market.An alternative solution proposed is to have everyone run a privately-owned server, similar to having a Lightning node at home with a full node accessed via a remote control mobile device. The writer proposes that private full nodes serving headers to a handful of weak devices is a good solution against problems in a future full of LN + Simplified Payment Verification (SPV) nodes. However, the inconvenience of having such a server at home prevents this from being a popular choice. The UX of connecting mobile LN clients to home full nodes needs to be made extremely easy so that centralized services cannot improve much on that step.Overall, the discussion highlights the importance of maintaining Bitcoin's security model by ensuring a supermajority of the economy is verifying their incoming transactions using their own full node. Various proposals have been made to combat potential harm to Bitcoin's security caused by externalizing the costs of security from light clients onto full nodes. The Bitcoin-dev mailing list has been discussing the importance of maintaining Bitcoin's security model while improving the user experience of connecting mobile Lightning Network clients to home full nodes.</summary>
